.TH SIMPLE_SHELL 1 "May 2026" "simple_shell" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
simple_shell \- simple UNIX command line interpreter
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B simple_shell
.br
.B simple_shell
.I filename
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B simple_shell
is a simple UNIX command line interpreter written in C.

It reads commands from standard input, parses them, searches for executable
programs, creates child processes, and executes commands using
.BR execve (2).

In interactive mode, the shell displays the prompt:
.B "($) "
before waiting for user input.

The shell can also read commands from a file when a filename is passed as an
argument.
.SH FEATURES
This shell supports:
.IP \(bu 2
Interactive and non-interactive modes
.IP \(bu 2
Command execution with arguments
.IP \(bu 2
PATH lookup
.IP \(bu 2
Environment printing with
.B env
.IP \(bu 2
.B exit
builtin
.IP \(bu 2
.B setenv
and
.B unsetenv
builtins
.IP \(bu 2
.B cd
builtin
.IP \(bu 2
Ctrl+C signal handling
.IP \(bu 2
File input mode
.SH BUILTINS
.TP
.B exit [status]
Exit the shell with an optional status.
.TP
.B env
Print the current environment.
.TP
.B setenv VARIABLE VALUE
Create or update an environment variable.
.TP
.B unsetenv VARIABLE
Remove an environment variable.
.TP
.B cd [DIRECTORY]
Change the current working directory.
If no directory is given, the shell changes to
.BR HOME .
.SH FILE INPUT
The shell can execute commands from a file:

.B ./simple_shell commands.txt

In this mode, no prompt is printed and commands are read from the file instead
of standard input.
.SH SIGNALS
When the user presses Ctrl+C, the shell does not exit. It prints a new prompt
and continues running.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
Run the shell:
.B ./simple_shell
.TP
Run a command:
.B ($) ls -l
.TP
Run a command with arguments:
.B ($) echo hello world
.TP
Print environment:
.B ($) env
.TP
Set environment variable:
.B ($) setenv NAME value
.TP
Unset environment variable:
.B ($) unsetenv NAME
.TP
Change directory:
.B ($) cd /tmp
.TP
Execute commands from a file:
.B ./simple_shell commands.txt
.SH RETURN VALUE
The shell returns the exit status of the last executed command when possible.
